profile_positions.description:
Container Centralen (CC) is an organization focused on providing logistical services and products with the goal to improve the supply chain of multiple clients that are located in a majority of the European countries.

During my time at CC, I have performed differing tasks at three departments in the company in a multilingual office with people from all over Europe. These tasks consisted of (but were not limited to):
- processing (both Dutch and foreign) customer requests by creating and effecting contracts necessary for the hiring (and buying) of CC-products and services;
- assisting (both Dutch and foreign) customers by answering questions and solving logistical issues;
- planning of deliveries, collections and returns of CC-products, and depot movements;
- invoicing (and crediting) of sold or hired CC-products and services.

Wageningen Marine Research (WMR) is the leading independent scientific research and advice institute with regards (but not limited) to marine monitoring, marine spatial planning, sustainable marine exploitation, nature-based solutions and food from the sea. By providing reliable scientific information, WMR contributes to more sustainable management, use and protection of natural resources in marine, coastal and freshwater areas.

My time at WMR was focused on the implementation of the landing obligation and the process of improving selectivity in Dutch demersal fisheries.
By performing a literature study, and conducting and analyzing multiple interviews with representatives of NGOs, fisheries organizations, legislative bodies and research institutes, the following was achieved:
- an inventarisation was constructed of factors that limit the possibility of achieving more selective Dutch demersal fisheries with the implementation of the landing obligation;
- an inventarisation was constructed of succesful management and technical measures in countries with already implemented discard bans;
- an assessment was made of which management and technical measures in countries with already implemented discard bans could be applicable to reach more selective Dutch demersal fisheries.

The Dutch Fishermen's Association (Nederlandse Vissersbond) is an organization representing the interests of Dutch professional fishermen, owners and onboard passengers, in the sea, coastal and inland fisheries. This representation is happening on a daily business in regional, national and international processes related (but not limited) to fisheries management and science, maritime spatial planning, certification of fishing practices, the Common Organisation of Markets, harbour facilities, development in fisheries communities, and crew matters.

Due to the recent MSC certification of the Dutch shrimp (Crangon crangon) fisheries in december 2017, my time with the Dutch Fishermen's Association has been spent on researching this industry and the support they have for the recent certification. 
By performing a literature study, and conducting and analyzing multiple interviews with fishermen of MSC certified shrimp fisheries, the following has been achieved: 
- an inventarisation has been constructed of the history, legislation, difficulties, innovations and the social economic value of the Dutch shrimp fisheries;
- the support of shrimp fisheries for the Dutch MSC certification has been made more apparent;
- recommendations have been formulated in the form of a policy brief concerning improvements of the trilateral managementplan for the Dutch, German and Danish MSC certified shrimp fisheries.

The Marine Stewardship Council (MSC) is a global non-profit organization, which leads the world's most prominent certification program for seafood sustainability. Through this program, consumers are made aware of (certified) sustainable fishing practices by looking for the MSC blue fish label on seafood products. This in turn encourages retailers to stock sustainably-sourced seafood and more fisheries to improve their fishing standards and become certified.

During my time at MSC, I have performed a research on the development of European fish stocks.
By collecting and analyzing data of European fish stocks that are managed by the Common Fisheries Policy (CFP) and/or are exploited by MSC certified fisheries, the following has been achieved:
- a database has been constructed with biological reference points of more than 100 European fish stocks for the period between 1945 and 2015;
- a graphical representation has been created for the development of the status of CFP managed fish stocks for those that are exploited by MSC certified fisheries and those that are not;
- the impact of MSC on the development of the status of CFP managed fish stocks has been made more apparent.
